{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Use British English|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox artefact | name = Coventry Sallet | image = [[File:Coventry Sallet HAGAM.jpg|center|300px]] | image2 = | image_caption = The Coventry Sallet | material =[[Steel]] | size = | writing = | created = c. 1460<ref name=ShafferyGravett>{{cite journal |first1=Peter Baron|last1=Shaffery |year=1982 |title=Early English helmets Part II |journal=Guns, weapons & Militaria |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=24–28 }} {{Citation |last=Gravett |first=Christopher |year=2001 |title=English Medieval Knight 1400-1500 |publisher=Osprey |isbn=978-1-84176-146-6|page =29}}</ref> | discovered = | location = [[Herbert Art Gallery and Museum|Herbert Art Gallery and Museum, Coventry]] | id = | registration = {{HAGAM-db|id=AR_1962_54|AR.1962.54}} }}
The '''Coventry Sallet''' is a 15th-century helmet now on display at [[Herbert Art Gallery and Museum]].<ref name=Shaffery /> English [[sallet]]s have been considered both rare and important.<ref>[[The Times]], 13 August 1927: Arms And Armour. New Exhibits At Victoria And Albert Museum</ref>
==Description== [[File:Herbert Art Gallery and Museum - Coventry Sallet.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The Sallet seen from the front]] The Sallet is 11 inches (27.9&nbsp;cm) in height, 12.25 inches (31.1&nbsp;cm) from front to back and is 7.75 inches (17.9&nbsp;cm) wide.<ref name=Shaffery>{{cite journal |first1=Peter Baron|last1=Shaffery |year=1982 |title=Early English helmets Part II |journal=Guns, weapons & Militaria |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=24–28 }}</ref> It weighs 5.25 pounds (2.4&nbsp;kg).<ref name=Shaffery /> It has a short tail and a jawbone type [[visor]] with a brow reinforcing.<ref name=blair>{{cite journal |last1=Blair |first1=C |year=1955 |title=The Blithfield Sallet |journal=Archaeological Journal |volume=CXI |pages=162–163|doi=10.1080/00665983.1954.10854081}}</ref> Stylistically, it is termed a "high crowned" helmet, different from the style usually seen in Italy or Germany.<ref name="Gravett 2001">{{Citation |last=Gravett |first=Christopher |year=2001 |title=English Medieval Knight 1400-1500 |publisher=Osprey |isbn=978-1-84176-146-6|page =29}}</ref> A plume holder was added to the helmet at some time after its manufacture.<ref name=blair />
==History==
The helmet was made around 1460, during the period of English civil conflict known as the [[Wars of the Roses]], and the armourer's marks suggest that it was made by an artisan originating from Italy.<ref name=ShafferyGravett>{{cite journal |first1=Peter Baron|last1=Shaffery |year=1982 |title=Early English helmets Part II |journal=Guns, weapons & Militaria |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=24–28 }} {{Citation |last=Gravett |first=Christopher |year=2001 |title=English Medieval Knight 1400-1500 |publisher=Osprey |isbn=978-1-84176-146-6|page =29}}</ref> During the 19th century it was used in Coventry’s [[Godiva Procession]].<ref name=Shaffery /> For a period it was kept on display at St Mary's Hall, Coventry, and is now shown at the city's [[Herbert Art Gallery and Museum]].<ref name=Shaffery />
Very few pieces of English-made armour survive from this period; the Coventry Sallet is believed to be the only example of its type in England.<ref name="Gravett 2001"/>
