{{More citations needed|date=February 2018}}[[File:Delahaye 235 Saoutchik Cabriolet1.jpg|thumb|[[Delahaye 235]] Cabriolet with Saoutchik bodywork]] [[File:1948 Cadillac Series 62 Saoutchik 3-position drophead (4321128358).jpg|thumb|1948 [[Cadillac Series 62]] of particularly flamboyant design]] Founded by cabinet maker Jacques Saoutchik (born Iakov Savtchuk in [[Russian Empire]] in 1880), '''Saoutchik''' was a top-class French coachbuilding company founded in 1906. In the 1930s the company became famous for their high quality and often extravagant designs. After Jacques died in 1955, the company passed into the hands of his son Pierre. With the great French luxury car manufacturers all going out of business, the market for the ostentatious Saoutchik designs evaporated and the company ceased trading in 1955.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Coachbuilders from past to present: Saoutchik | publisher = Coachbuild.com | url = http://www.coachbuild.com/index.php?option=com_gallery2&Itemid=50&g2_itemId=28052 | accessdate = 2010-10-19 }}</ref>
The company was known for designing flamboyant and expensive automobile bodies for classic brands such as [[Bugatti]], [[Delahaye]], [[Pegaso]], and others.
